<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920226-0029</DOCNO><DOCID>920226-0029.</DOCID><HL>   Agency to Resume Buying   Spot Oil for U.S. Reserve</HL><DATE>02/26/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)ENERGY DEPARTMENT (ERG)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Energy Department said it will resumepurchasing crude oil on the international spot market for theStrategic Petroleum Reserve.   The U.S. suspended oil purchases for the reserve in August1990, when Iraq invaded Kuwait. Later that year, thedepartment sold almost four million barrels in a test of theStrategic Reserve. In early 1991, it sold about 17 millionbarrels in the first emergency use of the facility.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman said the department has $671.3 millionavailable for buying oil, including proceeds from the salesand funds that were appropriated but never spent in earlieryears. Prices for the light crude oil the department wants tobuy have fallen below $19 a barrel.   The department said the oil will be acquired by theDefense Fuel Supply Center, the Defense Department'soil-purchasing arm. An open solicitation will be issued underwhich offers from oil suppliers will be received every twoweeks.   Energy Secretary James Watkins said the department willcontinue to explore leasing oil or other alternativeacquisition options for filling the reserve. Currently, thepetroleum reserve holds slightly more than 568 millionbarrels of crude in salt caverns along the Gulf Coast inTexas and Louisiana.</TEXT></DOC>